{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Unchecked ERC20 transfer return values allow phantom deposits and silent failed withdrawals","locations":["Staking.sol:123","Staking.sol:125","Staking.sol:129","Staking.sol:374","Staking.sol:376","Staking.sol:379","Staking.sol:498"],"claim":"`deposit`, `withdraw`, and `emergencyWithdraw` call `transferFrom`/`transfer` directly and ignore the returned boolean. For any accepted token that returns `false` instead of reverting, the contract still updates `balances`, checkpoints, pool sizes, and stable-coin accounting as if tokens moved successfully.","impact":"An attacker can create or use a token whose `transferFrom` silently fails for them, obtain stake credit without funding the pool, and later withdraw real liquidity deposited by other users of the same token. Failed outbound transfers can also leave users debited without actually receiving tokens.","paths":["Use a non-stable token that returns `false` on `transferFrom` for the attacker but still allows normal transfers for other users.","Call `deposit(token, amount, referrer)`; the contract records `amount` as staked even though it received nothing.","After honest users deposit the same token, call `withdraw` to receive real tokens from the contract while your original deposit was never funded."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Deposits credit the requested amount instead of the tokens actually received","locations":["Staking.sol:120","Staking.sol:127","Staking.sol:136","Staking.sol:149","Staking.sol:151","Staking.sol:153","Staking.sol:166","Staking.sol:181","Staking.sol:194","Staking.sol:214","Staking.sol:368","Staking.sol:371","Staking.sol:394","Staking.sol:396","Staking.sol:398"],"claim":"`deposit` increases `stableCoinBalances`, user `balances`, checkpoints, and epoch pool accounting by the caller-supplied `amount` without measuring how many tokens the contract actually received. Fee-on-transfer, deflationary, rebasing, or hook-based tokens therefore create over-credited positions.","impact":"A user can deposit a taxed or deflationary token, receive credit for more tokens than arrived, and later over-withdraw from that token pool once enough honest liquidity exists. The mismatch also corrupts epoch snapshots and reward-weight calculations.","paths":["Use a non-stable token that transfers only `amount - fee` to the staking contract.","Call `deposit(token, amount, referrer)`; internal accounting and checkpoints increase by `amount`, not by the net tokens received.","Later withdraw the full recorded balance, consuming liquidity supplied by later depositors."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Emergency withdrawal lets users recover principal while retaining stale epoch stake, and untouched pools are immediately eligible","locations":["Staking.sol:59","Staking.sol:487","Staking.sol:490","Staking.sol:495","Staking.sol:498","Staking.sol:508","Staking.sol:520","Staking.sol:558","Staking.sol:562"],"claim":"`emergencyWithdraw` only zeroes `balances[msg.sender][token]` and transfers tokens out; it does not update `balanceCheckpoints`, initialized `poolSize` snapshots, or any other epoch state consumed by `getEpochUserBalance` and `getEpochPoolSize`. Worse, `lastWithdrawEpochId[token]` defaults to `0`, and `getCurrentEpoch()` is already far greater than 10 because epochs started in June 2021, so any non-stable token pool with no prior successful normal withdrawal is immediately eligible for emergency exit.","impact":"A user can deposit into a fresh or untouched non-stable pool, immediately recover their principal through `emergencyWithdraw`, and still appear staked in epoch-based snapshot logic. Any rewards, voting weight, or accounting that relies on these getters can be stolen or distorted while the user no longer has funds at risk.","paths":["Use a non-stable token pool that has never had a successful normal `withdraw` recorded.","Call `deposit(token, amount, referrer)` to create checkpoints and initialize epoch snapshots.","Immediately call `emergencyWithdraw(token)`; the tokens are returned, but `getEpochUserBalance` and initialized pool snapshots still reflect the old stake."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex","merge-review"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Any small withdrawal can indefinitely grief the emergency-exit timer for an entire token pool","locations":["Staking.sol:59","Staking.sol:385","Staking.sol:487","Staking.sol:490"],"claim":"The emergency-exit gate is tracked in the single global variable `lastWithdrawEpochId[token]`. Every successful normal withdrawal, no matter which user performed it or how small the amount was, resets the timer for all users in that token pool.","impact":"An attacker with a dust position can keep `emergencyWithdraw` unavailable indefinitely by periodically withdrawing tiny amounts. If the pool later becomes dysfunctional or ordinary withdrawals stop working, all other stakers can be trapped without access to the advertised rescue path.","paths":["Acquire a minimal stake in a non-stable token pool.","Call `withdraw(token, dust)` at least once every 9 epochs.","All other users fail `emergencyWithdraw` because `getCurrentEpoch() - lastWithdrawEpochId[token]` never reaches 10."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Dormant pools become unusable until every missed epoch is initialized one transaction at a time","locations":["Staking.sol:142","Staking.sol:145","Staking.sol:387","Staking.sol:390","Staking.sol:466","Staking.sol:477","Staking.sol:479"],"claim":"When a pool is inactive for more than one epoch beyond the auto-initialized `current + 1` snapshot, both `deposit` and `withdraw` try to initialize only the current epoch. `manualEpochInit` then reverts because it requires `epochId - 1` to already be initialized, so skipped epochs must be backfilled strictly one by one.","impact":"After long inactivity, normal deposits and withdrawals revert until someone submits a separate `manualEpochInit` transaction for every missed epoch. This creates a practical denial of service and can leave a dormant pool unusable until an arbitrarily large catch-up sequence is executed.","paths":["Let a token pool sit idle for many epochs after its last activity.","Attempt `deposit` or `withdraw` in the current epoch; the internal `manualEpochInit(currentEpoch)` call reverts because `currentEpoch - 1` was never initialized.","Users must send one catch-up initialization transaction per missing epoch before normal operations resume."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-006","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Ignored Compound error codes can desynchronize stablecoin accounting from real liquidity","locations":["Staking.sol:262","Staking.sol:267","Staking.sol:321","Staking.sol:340","Staking.sol:356"],"claim":"Compound's `mint`, `redeemUnderlying`, and `redeem` return non-zero error codes on failure instead of reverting, but the contract ignores those return values everywhere. The staking logic therefore assumes stablecoins moved into or out of Compound even when Compound explicitly reported failure.","impact":"Paused markets, insufficient cash, or other Compound-side failures can leave `stableCoinBalances`, on-hand token balances, and cToken positions out of sync. Withdrawals can proceed after local balances are debited even though liquidity was never redeemed, interest extraction can malfunction, and later users can face failed or unfair withdrawals.","paths":["A stablecoin withdrawal calls `_redeemFromCompound(amount)`, but Compound returns a non-zero error code because redemption cannot be satisfied.","The function continues as if redemption succeeded and attempts to transfer tokens to the user anyway.","Accounting has already been reduced locally, so the contract can enter an inconsistent state and subsequent withdrawals or interest operations can fail."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[]}
